==Trivia==
*In the comics, Thor is the son of [[Odin]] and the primeval Earth goddess {{WPS|Gaea (Marvel Comics)|Gaea}}, rather than [[Frigga]].
*Thursday originates from Thor's Day, a day of the week named after Thor.
*Although Thor is briefly seen wearing his [[Winged Helmet|iconic winged silver helmet]] in the beginning of ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'', he quickly discards it. [[Chris Hemsworth]] admitted that the helmet was incredibly uncomfortable and was removed from the costume.
**In ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'', Thor briefly wears a [[Thor's Arena Helmet|collapsable helmet]] visually similar to his iconic winged helmet during his [[Duel in the Grand Arena|battle]] with [[Hulk]] in the [[Grandmaster]]'s [[Grand Arena|arena]].
*In the comics, Thor lost his left eye twice, both in futures as the King of Asgard; while in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]], he has lost his right eye while fighting [[Hela]], only to have it replaced with a [[Thor's Prosthetic Eye|prosthesis]].
*Thor is the third character in the Marvel Cinematic Universe shown to understand [[Groot]], the first being [[Rocket]] and the second being [[Star-Lord]].
*The red war paint adorning Thor's Sakaaran armor translates to "Lord of Thunder."{{Ref|MSVD}}

==Behind the Scenes==
*[[Chris Hemsworth]]'s brother, {{WPS|Liam Hemsworth}}, was originally on the shortlist to play Thor. After [[Kenneth Branagh]] decided to change the shortlist, he decided to consider only Chris. Liam gave Chris tips on how to get the role.
*[[Channing Tatum]], {{WPS|Paul Levesque}}, [[Daniel Craig]], {{WPS|Charlie Hunnam}}, [[Tom Hiddleston]], {{WPS|Alexander Skarsgård}} and {{WPS|Joel Kinnaman}} were considered for the role of Thor, before Chris Hemsworth was cast.<ref>[https://www.mtv.com/news/2593948/exclusive-no-thor-for-channing-tatum-studio-looking-for-someone-more-nordic-looking/ EXCLUSIVE: NO 'THOR' FOR CHANNING TATUM, STUDIO LOOKING FOR SOMEONE 'MORE NORDIC-LOOKING']</ref><ref>[https://www.pajiba.com/film_reviews/a-complete-list-of-all-the-actors-originally-considered-for-roles-in-the-marvel-universe.php A Complete List of All the Actors Originally Considered for Roles in the Marvel Universe]</ref>
*{{WPS|Cody Deal}} auditioned for the role of Thor, but didn't get the part. He did, however, end up playing a Norse version of the character in the film that was a mockbuster of the first movie, titled ''{{WPS|Almighty Thor}}''.<ref>[https://www.shockya.com/news/2011/02/22/exclusive-interview-with-almighty-thor-actor-cody-deal/ Exclusive Interview with Almighty Thor Actor Cody Deal]</ref>
*[[Chris Hemsworth]] was uncredited for his appearance in ''[[Doctor Strange (film)|Doctor Strange]]''.
*Thor in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] is the second live-action incarnation of the character, following an incarnation portrayed by {{WPS|Eric Allan Kramer}}.
*With the release of ''[[Thor: Love and Thunder]]'', Thor is the first lead character in the Marvel Cinematic Universe to have more than three solo films.
*[[Chris Hemsworth]] revealed in an interview with {{WPS|Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair}} that [[Kevin Smith]] inspired the decision for Thor to have short hair in ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'': ''"Hearing someone like Smith, who represents the fanboy world, was such a kick in the ass to change gears. We sort of had nothing to lose. People didn't expect what we did with it this time around."''<ref>[https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/thor-ragnarok-chris-hemsworth-mark-ruffalo-interview-best-thor-movie Thor: Ragnarok Proves Marvel Is Not Afraid to Learn from Its Mistakes]</ref>
*[[Michael Sims]], [[Matt LeFevour]], [[Bobby Holland Hanton]], [[Joel Michael Kramer]], [[Ben Wright]], [[Paul Lowe]], [[Daniel Stevens]], [[Ryan Tarran]], [[Chris Romrell]], [[Erik Schultz]], [[Dean Neistat]] and [[Justin Howell]] were stunt doubles for [[Chris Hemsworth]] in the role of Thor.
*[[Wade Speckels]], [[Danny Tomlinson]] and [[Ben Stabb]] were stand-ins for [[Chris Hemsworth]] in the role of Thor.
*[[Kane Schrader]] was a picture double for [[Chris Hemsworth]] in the role of Thor.

